    <br/>

    <table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%" align="center">
    <tr>
        <td bgcolor="#bbbbbb" width="1%" nowrap align="center">
            &nbsp;<font color="#ffffff"><b>Description</b></font>&nbsp;
        </td>
        <td>&nbsp;</td>
    </tr>
    </table>

    <table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td id="descriptionArea">
            <ul>
	<li>As a Developer, I want a stable and constrained database schema for Users, Roles, and Faculties so that I can persist identity data without risk of data corruption or orphaned records.</li>
	<li><b>Technical Scope:</b>
	<ul>
		<li>Initialize the PostgreSQL database and implement the DDL (Data Definition Language) for the core identity cluster.</li>
		<li><b>Tables:</b> <tt>Faculties</tt>, <tt>Roles</tt>, <tt>Users</tt>, and <tt>UserRoles</tt> (for M:M relationship if applicable, otherwise a <tt>RoleId</tt> FK in <tt>Users</tt>).</li>
		<li><b>Constraints:</b> Implement <tt>UUID</tt> as Primary Keys, <tt>UNIQUE</tt> on <tt>Users.Email</tt>, and <tt>NOT NULL</tt> on critical fields.</li>
		<li><b>Referential Integrity:</b> Set <tt>ON DELETE RESTRICT</tt> for Faculties to ensure no faculty is deleted while users are assigned to it.</li>
	</ul>
	</li>
	<li><b>Acceptance Criteria:</b>
	<ul>
		<li>All tables are generated with correct data types (e.g., <tt>timestamp with time zone</tt> for dates).</li>
		<li>The schema includes an <tt>IsActive</tt> boolean for soft-deletion of users.</li>
		<li>An ERD (Entity Relationship Diagram) is generated and exported to the documentation folder.</li>
		<li>The database is accessible to the Backend API via a connection string.</li>
	</ul>
	</li>
</ul>

            <br/>
        </td>
    </tr>
    </table>

