    <br/>

    <table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%" align="center">
    <tr>
        <td bgcolor="#bbbbbb" width="1%" nowrap align="center">
            &nbsp;<font color="#ffffff"><b>Description</b></font>&nbsp;
        </td>
        <td>&nbsp;</td>
    </tr>
    </table>

    <table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td id="descriptionArea">
            <ul>
	<li><b>User Story:</b> As a System User, I want my credentials to be hashed using the Argon2id algorithm so that my identity remains protected against brute-force and rainbow table attacks.</li>
	<li><b>Technical Scope:</b>
	<ul>
		<li>Implement an <tt>IPasswordHasher</tt> interface and an <tt>Argon2PasswordHasher</tt> implementation.</li>
		<li><b>Parameters:</b> Use a Salt size of 128-bit, Time cost of 3 iterations, and Memory cost of 64MB (standard for modern .NET security).</li>
		<li>Develop the <tt>AuthService.VerifyCredentials(LoginDto dto)</tt> logic to compare incoming plain-text with stored hashes.</li>
	</ul>
	</li>
	<li><b>Acceptance Criteria:</b>
	<ul>
		<li>Passwords are <b>never</b> stored in the database in plain text.</li>
		<li>The hashing process is non-deterministic (unique salt per user).</li>
		<li>The system returns a $401\text
{ Unauthorized}
<p>$ for invalid credentials without revealing whether the email or password was wrong (Security best practice).</p></li>
		<li>The implementation passes a unit test validating that a known password matches its generated hash.</li>
	</ul>
	</li>
</ul>

            <br/>
        </td>
    </tr>
    </table>

